rca 1302","about 1300":"circa 1300","1328":"1328","Ireland":"Ierland","Fermoy, Cork, Munster, Ireland":"Fermoy, County Cork, Ierland"},"en":{"about 1300–1374":"about 1300–1374","1300–1374":"1300–1374","–Male":"Deceased","1328–1350":"1328–1350","1350–1387":"1350–1387","1255–1302":"1255–1302","–Female":"Deceased","before 1358":"before 1358","before 1300":"before 1300","1374":"1374","Bef 1358":"before 1358","1350":"1350","1348":"1348","1302":"1302","1300":"1300","1255":"1255","1387":"1387","about 1302":"about 1302","about 1300":"about 1300","1328":"1328","Ireland":"Ireland","Fermoy, Cork, Munster, Ireland":"Fermoy, County Cork, Ireland","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Roche","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Brendan, Aidan, Declan, Eamonn, Fergus, Fionnuala, Kevin Patrick, Liam.","Irish (Munster) and English (of Norman origin): variant of   Roach  . Compare   Roch  .","French: topographic name for someone who lived by a rocky outcrop or crag, from Old French <i>roche</i> ‘rock’. In North America, this surname is also a shortened form of the variant   Laroche   2. Compare   Deroche  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Laroche","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Andre, Armand, Fernand, Normand, Pierre, Jacques, Laurent, Adrien, Cecile, Germain, Marcel.","French:","habitational name from any of numerous places in various parts of France named Laroche or La Roche, from Old French <i>roche</i> ‘rock’, with feminine definite article <i>la</i>."]},{"name":"Larocque","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Andre, Armand, Fernand, Henri, Marcel, Normand, Valmore, Yves, Achille, Amie, Donat, Emile.","French: habitational name from La Ro(c)que, the name of several places in various parts of France, from a regional variant of <i>roche</i> ‘rock’ (see   Roche  , compare   Laroche  ), with feminine definite article <i>la</i>. Compare   Laroque  .","Altered form of southern French <b>Roquebrune</b> or of its variant <b>Rocquebrune</b>: habitational name from Ro(c)quebrune, the name of several places in the southern part of France. The surname <i>Roquebrune</i> is rare in France, while the variant <i>Rocquebrune</i> is extinct there. Compare   Larock  ,   Lerocque  ,   Rockburn  , and   Rocque   1."]},{"name":"Rochet","meanings":["French: diminutive of   Roche  , a topographic name meaning ‘rock’, or a habitational name from (Le) Rochet, the name of several places in various parts of France.","Catalan: of French origin (see above). This surname is also found in the Dominican Republic and Puerto Rico."]},{"name":"Rochat","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Andre, Monique, Philippe, Pierre.","French: topographic name from a diminutive of Old French <i>roche</i> ‘rock’ (see   Roche   2), or a habitational name from Le Rochat, the name of several places in the eastern part of France."]},{"name":"Roach","meanings":["English:","of Norman origin, from Old French and Middle English <i>roche</i> ‘rock, cliff, promontory’, sometimes a translation of   Stone  . The surname may have been topographic, denoting someone who lived on or by a prominent rock or rocky place, or a habitational name for someone who lived or came from a place so named, such as one of those called Roque or Roche(s) in Normandy and neighboring regions, or Roche in Cornwall, Roach Farm in Clyst Hydon (Devon), or Roch in Pembrokeshire (see   Roch  ).","in Lancashire perhaps referring to the River Roch, which runs through Rochdale; the river name is probably a back-formation from <i>Recedham</i>, an early name for Rochdale recorded in 1086, derived from Old English <i>reced</i> ‘building, house, hall’ + <i>hām</i> ‘village, homestead’. Alternatively, the Lancashire name could be a shortened form of the now rare or extinct surname <b>Rochdale</b> alias <b>Rachedale</b>, <i>Rachdall</i>, a habitational name from Rochdale (Lancashire). From the 18th century onward the name is difficult to distinguish from   Roch  , borne by Irish migrants to South Lancashire, especially Liverpool."]},{"name":"Roquet","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Alain, Camille.","French: topographic name from a diminutive of <i>roche</i> ‘rock’ (see   Roche   and   Roque  ), or a habitational name from (Le) Roquet, the name of several places in various parts of France."]},{"name":"Rochez","meanings":["Walloon and French: variant of   Roche   2 or   Rocher  ."]}]},{"name":"David","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Biblical name, borne by the greatest of all the kings of Israel, whose history is recounted with great vividness in the first and second books of Samuel and elsewhere. As a boy he killed the giant Philistine Goliath with his slingshot. As king of Judah, and later of all Israel, he expanded the power of the Israelites and established the security of their kingdom. He was also noted as a poet, many of the Psalms being attributed to him. The Hebrew derivation of the name is uncertain; it is said by some to represent a nursery word meaning ‘darling’. It is a very popular Jewish name, but is almost equally common among Gentiles in the English-speaking world. It is particularly common in Wales and Scotland, having been borne by the patron saint of Wales (  see  Dewi   ) and by two medieval kings of Scotland."],"variants":[]},{"name":"de","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Variant of   Dev ."],"variants":[{"name":"Deborah","meanings":["Biblical name (meaning ‘bee’ in Hebrew), borne by the nurse of Rebecca (Genesis 35:8) and by a woman judge and prophet (Judges 4–5) who led the Israelites to victory over the Canaanites. It has always been popular as a Jewish name. It was in use among Christians by the mid 16th century and was taken up by the Puritans in the 17th century, in part because the bee was a symbol of industriousness. Since then it has enjoyed enormous popularity, peaking in the 1960s. Among other famous bearers is the actress  Deborah Kerr  (  1921–2007 )."]}]},{"name":"la","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["‘Orchid’."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"David de la Roche Lord Roche was born about 1300, in Ireland as the son of Alexander de la Roche and Mrs Alexander de la Roche. He married Anna Fleming in 1348, in Fermoy, County Cork, Ireland. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in 1374, in Fermoy, County Cork, Ireland, at the age of 75."},"et":{"about 1300–1374":"umbes 1300–1374","1300–1374":"1300–1374","–Male":"Surnud","1328–1350":"1328–1350","1350–1387":"1350–1387","1255–1302":"1255–1302","–Female":"Surnud","before 1358":"enne 1358","before 1300":"enne 1300","1374":"1374","Bef 1358":"enne 1358","1350":"1350","1348":"1348","1302":"1302","1300":"1300","1255":"1255","1387":"1387","about 1302":"umbes 1302","about 1300":"umbes 1300","1328":"1328","Ireland":"Iirimaa","Fermoy, Cork, Munster, Ireland":"Fermoy, County Cork, Iirimaa"},"fi":{"about 1300–1374":"noin 1300–1374","1300–1374":"1300–1374","–Male":"Kuollut","1328–1350":"1328–1350","1350–1387":"1350–1387","1255–1302":"1255–1302","–Female":"Kuollut","before 1358":"ennen vuotta 1358","before 1300":"ennen vuotta 1300","1374":"1374","Bef 1358":"ennen vuotta 1358","1350":"1350","1348":"1348","1302":"1302","1300":"1300","1255":"1255","1387":"1387","about 1302":"noin 1302","about 1300":"noin 1300","1328":"1328","Ireland":"Irlanti","Fermoy, Cork, Munster, Ireland":"Fermoy, County Cork, Irlanti"},"fr":{"about 1300–1374":"environ 1300–1374","1300–1374":"1300–1374","–Male":"Décédé","1328–1350":"1328–1350","1350–1387":"1350–1387","1255–1302":"1255–1302","–Female":"Décédée","before 1358":"avant 1358","before 1300":"avant 1300","1374":"1374","Bef 1358":"avant 1358","1350":"1